snippet.textDisplay:
The lessons learnt when perhaps nine or ten years old , are still with him: Twist and weave, lose points rather than take a head shot. ( he was hit with very few head shots of worth) His early training combined with a lot of Bag work , made his opponent look a bit one dimensional. I like a body puncher, after a good going over, the result is a knockdown rather than a KO . I would rather see a Boxer taking the count , out of breath on one knee, rather than a KO. The combination of : Skill, size, agility, measured pace, drained his opponent from round one .DW
Instead of altering his game plan, he just kept digging a deeper hole for himself.

The good thing to come out of this fight,( IMO) Is perhaps a shift away from just " Lack of skill hard hitters" to " Body punchers , and tactical boxing"



What makes Boxing for me is the actual fight on the night re clash of different styles, this fight was a great example of that. No excuses can be made on either side, they were both at the top of their game.

snippet.textDisplay: respect to both Fury and Wilder. Both are great fighters, and anyone who says Wilder isn't doesn't have a clue about boxing.
